    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>Jany 29/57</date>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>, Dr Sir/</p>
            <p>I herewith send a certificate of<lb/> Deposit for the following payments.<lb/>
                <persName>Isidire Raphael</persName> 6.00 <persName>Soln Weil</persName> 3.00<lb/>
                He will pay the rest another time.</p>
            <p><persName>H. B. Heerts</persName> Amt 6.00 &amp; <persName>Rev A. Lev</persName>
                6.00<lb/> making in all $33.00 &amp; after taking off<lb/> 1.98/100 for Delivery
                &amp; 12/100 for Express there<lb/> remains $30.10 which I now send you<lb/> It is
                strange that I was only charged<lb/> 12 cents for bringing the parcel when you
                said<lb/> that you had not paid for it, while the time<lb/> before there was a
                double payment.<lb/>
                <persName>J. Bernhard</persName> says that he paid for the<lb/> 2 Books on Delivery,
                as the Boy would not<lb/> leave them without the Money.</p>
            <p>It is very hard to get in any money<lb/> no matter how often you call for it<lb/>
                Some are sick &amp; cannot see you, others<lb/> are out of the city &amp; some
                cannot or will<lb/> not pay. <persName>Rittersland</persName> promised me<lb/> to
                look after his account or at least</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>she promised which is better, but<lb/> they have been unfortunate in losing<lb/> a
                Daughter. <persName>Isidore Raphall</persName> wants<lb/> some numbers which he says
                you<lb/> promised him. <persName>Sedgewick</persName> the most<lb/> Plausible man
                living, I am sure will<lb/> not pay he has fooled me so often</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>P. Joseph</persName> cannot be found,<lb/> have you any
                clue to his whereabouts?<lb/> I shall expect my commission<lb/> on <persName>Lewis
                    Solomons</persName> bill whatever<lb/> the amount is which he paid you<lb/> as I
                have called on him at least<lb/> 15 times for the money &amp; I think<lb/> I am
                fairly entitled to it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The parcel came to hand yesterday<lb/> &amp; I had to send it up
                town for I am<lb/> really sick with a cold which has <lb/>stuck to me above a
                month.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now with regard to your<lb/> new publications I have to inform
                you<lb/> that I have solicited a good many<lb/> people who I thought were
                likely<lb/> to become subscribers, but I could<lb/> not obtain even <hi
                    rend="underline">one</hi>. in one<lb/> instance <persName>Mr Isaacs</persName>
                was present</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>&amp; heard the refusals &amp; met with<lb/>
                <persName>Mr B nathan</persName> &amp; some one else<lb/> did indeed tell me that
                they had<lb/> already put down their names.<lb/> So as far as I am concerned I
                have<lb/> failed totally. If anything else<lb/> should occur to me down town<lb/>
                shall write it before I send this Letter<lb/> meantime I am Dr Sir yours very
                truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <persName role="author">M. Rubenstein</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Send me the price of your better bound<lb/> Quarto Bibles in case I should be<lb/>
                asked for one &amp; the percentage you<lb/> allow on each</p>
        </body>
